  "local_port": 48670,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some funniest Indian English phrases that people use?",
  "response": "Indian English, often referred to as \"Hinglish,\" is a delightful blend of Hindi (and other Indian languages) and English, resulting in some unique and often humorous phrases. Here are some of the funniest and most commonly used ones:\n\n1. **\"Do the needful.\"**  \n   - A classic Indian English phrase meaning \"Take the necessary action.\" It sounds formal but is used in the most casual contexts.\n\n2. **\"What is your good name?\"**  \n   - Instead of just asking, \"What is your name?\" Indians often add \"good\" to make it sound more polite.\n\n3. **\"Passing out\" instead of \"graduating.\"**  \n   - Example: \"I passed out from college last year.\" It makes it sound like you fainted from the stress of exams!\n\n4. **\"Only na!\"**  \n   - Used to emphasize something, like \"It\u2019s just there only na!\" The \"na\" is a Hindi addition for emphasis.\n\n5. **\"Kindly revert.\"**  \n   - Instead of \"Please reply,\" Indians often say \"Kindly revert,\" which technically means \"go back to a previous state.\"\n\n6. **\"Prepone\"**  \n   - The opposite of \"postpone.\" If a meeting is moved earlier, Indians say, \"Let\u2019s prepone it.\"\n\n7. **\"Out of station.\"**  \n   - Instead of saying \"I\u2019m out of town,\" people say, \"I\u2019m out of station.\" It sounds like you\u2019re a train pulling out of a railway station.\n\n8. **\"Timepass\"**  \n   - Something done to pass the time, like \"Watching TikTok videos is just timepass.\"\n\n9. **\"Keep it in the fridge\" instead of \"Put it in the fridge.\"**  \n   - It\u2019s not about keeping it there; it\u2019s about putting it there first!\n\n10. **\"Today morning\" and \"Yesterday night.\"**  \n    - Instead of saying \"This morning\" or \"Last night,\" Indians will often say \"Today morning\" and \"Yesterday night.\"\n\n11. **\"Cousin brother/sister.\"**  \n    - Indians specify \"cousin brother\" or \"cousin sister\" to clarify gender, even though \"cousin\" alone suffices.\n\n12. **\"Mention not.\"**  \n    - A polite way of saying \"You\u2019re welcome,\" but it sounds like you\u2019re asking someone not to mention something.\n\n13. **\"Shifted to US.\"**  \n    - Instead of saying \"I moved to the US,\" Indians often say, \"I shifted to the US,\" as if they\u2019re a piece of furniture being relocated.\n\n14. **\"Hotel\" for \"restaurant.\"**  \n    - Indians often call a standalone restaurant a \"hotel,\" leading to confusion when foreigners think they\u2019re being taken to stay overnight.\n\n15. **\"Do one thing.\"**  \n    - A phrase often used to suggest a solution, like \"Do one thing, just call them and ask.\" It\u2019s oddly specific but widely understood.\n\n16. **\"Discuss about.\"**  \n    - Instead of \"discuss,\" Indians often say \"discuss about,\" like \"Let\u2019s discuss about the plan.\"\n\n17. **\"Bio-data\" instead of \"resume.\"**  \n    - Used to describe someone\u2019s CV, but it sounds more like a scientific analysis of a person.\n\n18. **\"Sitting on my head.\"**  \n    - A dramatic way of saying someone is annoying you, like \"My boss is sitting on my head these days.\"\n\n19. **\"Traffic is jammed.\"**  \n    - Instead of saying \"There\u2019s a traffic jam,\" people often say \"Traffic is jammed,\" as if the traffic itself is stuck in a jar.\n\n20. **\"Healthful\" instead of \"healthy.\"**  \n    - Example: \"This food is very healthful.\" It sounds wholesome but a bit off to native English speakers.\n\nThese phrases are a testament to the creativity and adaptability of Indian English, and while they might sound funny to native English speakers, they\u2019re perfectly normal in India!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
